### Entry point

`render/app.jsx` is required. It must include `export default` — the renderer mounts that default export as the artifact's root component.

```jsx
/** @datus-title Northeast 2026 Q1 Sales Review */
import React from 'react';
import KpiBanner from './kpi-banner';
import RevenueTrend from './revenue-trend';
import SalesTable from './sales-table';
import Footer from './footer';

export default function App() {
  return (
    <div style={{ padding: 32, fontFamily: 'system-ui' }}>
      <KpiBanner />
      <RevenueTrend />
      <SalesTable />
      <Footer />
    </div>
  );
}
```

The optional `/** @datus-title ... */` annotation at the top is used by the standalone viewer for the browser tab title; falls back to the artifact slug when absent.

### Allowed imports

| Module | Version | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `react` | `^18.2.0` | `useState`, `useEffect`, `useRef`, `useMemo`, `useCallback`, `useContext`, `createContext`, plus the default `React` namespace |
| `@datus/web-artifact` | runtime-provided | `useDatusArtifact`, `AnimateOnVisible` (see "Motion & animation"), `ChartCard` (see "Canonical component shape" + "Card props"), `ChartEntryMore` (escape hatch — `ChartCard` already embeds it), `Skeleton`, `ErrorBlock` (see "Loading & error placeholders") |
| `recharts` | `^3.8.1` | any named export (`AreaChart`, `LineChart`, `BarChart`, `RadarChart`, `PieChart`, `ResponsiveContainer`, `Tooltip`, `XAxis`, `YAxis`, `CartesianGrid`, `Area`, `Line`, `Bar`, `Radar`, `Pie`, `Cell`, etc.). **v3, not v2** — see the v3 notes below. |
| `lucide-react` | `^0.563.0` | any icon component (`User`, `TrendingUp`, `Banknote`, `Globe`, `Landmark`, …). **Use these instead of emoji** — see the "Iconography & emoji" section below. |
| `d3-format` | `^3.1.2` | `format` — build numeric / currency / percent / SI-prefix formatters |
| `dayjs` | `^1.11.20` | default `dayjs` factory + `.format(pattern)` |
| `'./<sibling>'` or `'../<path>'` | — | resolves to a file under `render/`. `./kpi-banner` → `render/kpi-banner.jsx`; `./charts/trend` → `render/charts/trend.jsx`. Extensions optional; `/index.jsx` fallback supported. |

Do **not** import from: `react-dom`, `next/*`, `react-router*`, state-management (`zustand`, `redux`, `jotai`), CSS-in-JS (`styled-components`, `emotion`), data-fetching (`swr`, `react-query`), or utility libraries (`lodash`, `date-fns`, `moment`). Reimplement what you need inline. The validator rejects every other bare specifier; the iframe runtime would also throw.

Relative paths must stay under `render/` — `../../../escape` is rejected.

**recharts is v3, not v2** — avoid these v2-only patterns the model tends to reach for:

- No `activeIndex` / `activeShape` on `<Pie>` / `<Bar>` / `<Scatter>` (removed in v3). To emphasize a slice/bar, drive its color from data via `<Cell fill>` instead.
- `<Pie blendStroke>` removed → use `stroke="none"`.
- SVG has no z-index; paint order follows JSX order. Put `<Tooltip>` **after** `<Legend>` in JSX so the tooltip renders on top.

### Import every name you reference

Every JSX component (`<Cell>`, `<Legend>`, `<Coffee>`) and every helper (`useMemo`, `formatCurrency`, `N`) used in a file must appear in a named import at the top of *that same file*. `recharts`, `lucide-react`, and `@datus/web-artifact` do not register globals — a missing import surfaces at render time as `ReferenceError: <name> is not defined` and crashes the whole artifact. `validate_render` only checks that the import *paths* resolve; it does not check that every JSX identifier is imported, so the burden is on you.

Before saving a file, scan its body and JSX for every capitalized component (Recharts primitives like `<Cell>`, Lucide icons like `<Coffee>`) plus every helper call (`N`, `formatCurrency`, …) and confirm each one is in one of the file's `import { ... }` lines. The most common miss: adding `<Cell>` inside `<Bar>` / `<Pie>` for per-row coloring while leaving `Cell` out of the existing `recharts` import.

### Canonical component shape

Every chart / table / KPI component in `render/` is one `<ChartCard>` from `@datus/web-artifact` wrapping the chart body. **Copy this skeleton when you author a new component.** ChartCard owns the card chrome (white surface, 12-radius, asymmetric padding, flex-column stretch) and the chart-actions menu (View SQL / Export CSV / JSON / PNG / etc.). You only author the data layer and the chart body inside.

```jsx
import { useMemo } from 'react';
import { useDatusArtifact, ChartCard, AnimateOnVisible, Skeleton, ErrorBlock } from '@datus/web-artifact';
import { ResponsiveContainer, LineChart, Line, XAxis, YAxis, Tooltip } from 'recharts';
import { N } from './shared/formatters';

function RevenueTrendCard() {
  // 1. Data hooks — every `useQuerySql` at the top, before any early return.
  const { useQuerySql } = useDatusArtifact();
  const { isLoading, errorMessage, data, refetch } = useQuerySql('queries/revenue_by_month');

  // 2. Derived data — `useMemo` with stable deps; coerce numerics with N().
  const rows = useMemo(
    () => (data?.rows ?? []).map(r => ({ ...r, revenue: N(r.revenue) })),
    [data],
  );

  // 3. Early returns — only AFTER every hook above. Render loading / error
  //    placeholders here; never inline a hook into the JSX below.
  if (isLoading) return <Skeleton minHeight={300} />;
  if (errorMessage) return <ErrorBlock msg={errorMessage} onRetry={refetch} />;

  // 4. JSX — ChartCard owns the wrapper, header strip, and menu. You just
  //    pass chartId / sqlId / chartType + data (for the export menu).
  return (
    <ChartCard
      chartId="revenue_by_month"
      sqlId="queries/revenue_by_month"
      chartType="line"
      title="Revenue trend"
      data={data}
    >
      <AnimateOnVisible minHeight={300}>
        <ResponsiveContainer width="100%" height={300}>
          <LineChart data={rows}>
            <XAxis dataKey="month" />
            <YAxis />
            <Tooltip />
            <Line type="monotone" dataKey="revenue" stroke="#6051F5" />
          </LineChart>
        </ResponsiveContainer>
      </AnimateOnVisible>
    </ChartCard>
  );
}
```

The four sections are not optional ordering — they are the only ordering React permits:

1. **Data hooks (`useQuerySql`)** — first, never inside a conditional.
2. **Derived data (`useMemo` / `useCallback`)** — also hooks; same constraint.
3. **Early returns (`if (isLoading) return …`)** — only after every hook.
4. **JSX** — references derived data by name. No hook calls inside JSX.

`AnimateOnVisible` and the chart primitives are normal JSX — they live inside `<ChartCard>` in section 4. **Do not write `useRef(null)` or wrap the card in your own `<div ref={cardRef}>`** — ChartCard owns the screenshot root and the chart-actions menu internally.

### Card props

`<ChartCard>` requires three declarative props on every chart card. They are read at render time by the chart-actions menu and also act as the stable identifier the runtime uses if a follow-up turn pins an edit to this specific chart (see "Targeted single-card edits" in the dashboard prompt).

| Prop | Required | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `chartId` | yes | Stable id, unique across `render/*.jsx`. Convention: matches the sqlId basename (`queries/revenue_by_month` → `chartId="revenue_by_month"`). Must match `^[a-z0-9_]{1,64}$`. |
| `sqlId` | yes | Same literal you passed to `useQuerySql`, in `queries/<slug>` form. ChartCard forwards it to the inner chart-actions menu for View SQL / Export. |
| `chartType` | yes | One of: `'bar' \| 'line' \| 'area' \| 'pie' \| 'scatter' \| 'radar' \| 'composed' \| 'radial-bar' \| 'treemap' \| 'funnel' \| 'gauge' \| 'heatmap' \| 'waterfall' \| 'table' \| 'kpi' \| 'custom'`. Picks the value that matches the chart primitive you render below. The first seven map directly to recharts components (`BarChart`, `LineChart`, `AreaChart`, `PieChart`, `ScatterChart`, `RadarChart`, `ComposedChart`); `radial-bar` / `treemap` / `funnel` are also recharts-native (`RadialBarChart`, `Treemap`, `FunnelChart`). `gauge` / `heatmap` / `waterfall` aren't recharts-native — render them via hand-rolled SVG (or a `radial-bar` subset for gauges); the enum value is still preferred over `'custom'` because it carries intent that the edit-time LLM uses. Use `'custom'` only for shapes that don't match any of the named entries. Surfaced to ``validate_render`` only — it is **not** included in the targeted-edit envelope; the LLM reads the JSX before editing anyway. |
| `data` | recommended | The `data` field from the matching `useQuerySql(sqlId, params)`. Required if the chart-actions menu needs to expose View SQL / Export CSV / Export JSON; PNG export still works without it. |
| `params` | recommended in dashboard mode | The same params object you passed to `useQuerySql`. ChartCard does not consume it — it gets snapshotted into the edit-intent payload so the follow-up LLM call sees the filter state the user was looking at. |
| `title` | optional | `string` or `ReactNode` (icon + text). Renders as the card heading. |
| `titleRight` | optional | Extra title-strip content rendered to the LEFT of the built-in chart-actions menu. Use sparingly — most cards don't need it. |
| `hideMenu` | optional | Set on pure-presentation cards that shouldn't show the chart-actions menu. |
| `style` / `className` | optional | Standard passthroughs. |

**Do not pass `__sourcePath`.** It is auto-injected by the artifact runtime at module-load time; any value you set is overwritten.

### Data layer — `useDatusArtifact`

All data access goes through one hook:

```jsx
import { useDatusArtifact } from '@datus/web-artifact';

const { useQuerySql } = useDatusArtifact();
const { isLoading, errorMessage, data, refetch } = useQuerySql('queries/account_activity_by_city');
```

Returns:
- `isLoading: boolean` — true until the artifact resolves.
- `errorMessage: string | null` — non-null when the sqlId is unpublished or the JSON is malformed.
- `data: ISqlQueryResult | null` — null until ready.
- `refetch: () => void` — re-runs the query against the underlying provider, ignoring any in-memory cache. Pass into `<ErrorBlock onRetry={refetch}>` to wire up the placeholder's Retry button.

```ts
type ColumnSemanticType = 'string' | 'integer' | 'number' | 'date' | 'boolean';
interface IQueryColumnMeta { name: string; type: ColumnSemanticType }
interface ISqlQueryResult {
  executed_at: string;
  datasource: string;
  row_count: number;
  columns: IQueryColumnMeta[];
  rows: Array<Record<string, unknown>>;
}
```

Always read rows as `data?.rows ?? []` and columns as `data?.columns ?? []`. Coerce numeric cells with `Number(value)` before arithmetic — BIGINT columns may serialize as JS `BigInt`, which breaks Recharts and `Math.*`.

#### sqlId conventions

- `useQuerySql(spec)` accepts a literal string `'queries/<slug>'` (the canonical form) or a template string built from a finite enumeration declared as a `const` in the same file:

  ```jsx
  const AVAILABLE_MONTHS = ['2025-01', '2025-02', '2025-03'];
  const [month, setMonth] = useState('2025-01');
  const { data } = useQuerySql(`queries/revenue_by_month_${month}`);
  ```

  The validator only static-checks **literal** spec strings. Template strings resolve at runtime; the iframe will surface unknown slugs as `errorMessage`.

- One `useQuerySql` declaration per query, in the data-hooks block (section 1 of the Canonical component shape).
- Render a skeleton placeholder when `isLoading`; an inline error block when `errorMessage`; the chart/table otherwise. Those `return` statements live in section 3 — after the full hook block, never between hooks.

#### Hook safety

All hook-related rules collapse to a single invariant — the React rule that breaks the most artifacts. Read it twice.

- **Every `use*` hook is called unconditionally, in the same order, at the top of the function body.** That includes `useMemo`, `useState`, `useCallback`, `useEffect`, `useContext`, `useQuerySql`, and every custom hook.
- **No hook call may appear inside JSX.** Declare derived values above and reference them by name from the JSX below.
- **No hook call may appear after an early return.** Place `if (isLoading) return …`, `if (errorMessage) return …`, `if (rows.length === 0) return null` *after* every hook — never between two hooks.

Violating any of these surfaces as `Minified React error #310` ("Rendered more hooks than during the previous render") and crashes the whole artifact. **The Canonical component shape above is the proof shape — if your code structurally matches it, you cannot trip #310.**

Anti-pattern most often emitted by lower-tier models — second hook reached only on the data-non-empty render, crashes the *next* render once data arrives:

```jsx
function YoYSummary() {
  const { useQuerySql } = useDatusArtifact();
  const { data } = useQuerySql('queries/yoy_summary');
  const rows = data?.rows ?? [];
  if (rows.length === 0) return null;
  const total = useMemo(() => rows.reduce((s, r) => s + r.value, 0), [rows]);  // ✗ #310: useMemo reached only after the early return
  return <span>{total}</span>;
}
```

### Aggregation correctness — fan-out is the bug; MAX/MIN are safe

Whenever a query both **JOINs a "header" table to a "detail" / "line-item" child table** (1:N relationship — one row in the parent can match many rows in the child) **and** aggregates a column from the header side, you have a high probability of a silent fan-out bug. This rule is schema-agnostic: it applies whether the tables are `orders`/`order_items`, `sessions`/`events`, `accounts`/`transactions`, `posts`/`comments`, or any other parent-detail pair.

| Aggregate over header column under 1:N JOIN | Behavior | Verdict |
|---|---|---|
| `SUM(parent.col)` | Inflated by child cardinality — each parent row counted once per child | **Wrong** |
| `COUNT(parent.col)` (non-null) | Same inflation | **Wrong** |
| `COUNT(*)` | Counts joined rows, not parents | **Wrong** |
| `AVG(parent.col)` | Numerator and denominator both inflate; for **uniform** fan-out the mean is unchanged, but for **non-uniform** fan-out (parents have differing child counts) it silently becomes a child-weighted mean rather than a parent-equal-weight mean | **Silently biased — treat as wrong** |
| `STDDEV` / `VAR` / `PERCENTILE` over `parent.col` | Distribution re-weighted by child counts | **Wrong** |
| `MAX(parent.col)` / `MIN(parent.col)` | Idempotent under row duplication — value unchanged | **Safe** |
| `COUNT(DISTINCT parent.pk)` | DISTINCT collapses duplicates | **Safe** |

Detection signals — applicable regardless of domain or table names:

1. The SELECT/HAVING aggregates a column from the "1" side of a 1:N relationship that the FROM clause also reaches into via JOIN.
2. Two-level chains: `JOIN A → B → C` where the metric is on A and B is the detail of A — fan-out multiplies through every intermediate detail table, so each A.row gets attributed to every C-grouping it transitively touches.
3. The same query both produces a header aggregate (e.g. `SUM(parent.amount)`) and reads a detail column (e.g. `child.sku`, `child.qty`) — the JOIN serves the detail-side need but breaks the aggregate.

Mandatory fix paths — pick the one that matches your intent:

- **(a) Drop the child JOIN** if you don't need any column from it. This is the right fix for KPI-style aggregates that should run against the header table alone.
- **(b) Pre-aggregate the child in a CTE** so the post-CTE JOIN is 1:1. Right when you genuinely need per-parent rollups of child data.
- **(c) `SUM(DISTINCT parent.col)`** is rarely correct — only valid when `parent.pk` is in the SELECT/GROUP BY and the SUM target is unique per parent. Do not reach for it as a shortcut.

When uncertain about cardinality, verify with `execute_sql` before saving:

```sql
-- compare these two — if joined_rows >> parent_rows, every header aggregate is wrong by that ratio
SELECT COUNT(*) FROM <parent_table>   /* with the same WHERE the final query uses */;
SELECT COUNT(*) FROM <parent_table> JOIN <child_table> ON <fk> /* same WHERE */;
```

Fan-out is a **bug to be fixed**, not a caveat to disclose. Do NOT save a query that has the bug and then declare it in `caveats` — the caveats field is for legitimate semantic choices the reader needs to know about (LEFT JOIN keeping zero-child parents, NULL-handling, time-window assumptions, etc.), not for known wrong arithmetic.

### Unit conventions — probe; don't guess; ask when ambiguous

Schemas almost never label the **unit** of a numeric column. The same `revenue` column can hold dollars, cents, basis points, or thousands; `latency` can be ms or s; `rate` can be 0.05 or 5.0. Guessing wrong silently propagates a 10× / 100× / 1000× error through every downstream KPI and chart, and no validator catches it because the SQL is syntactically perfect.

**Mandatory probe** for any money / ratio / duration / count column whose name does **not** explicitly declare its unit (no `_cents` / `_usd` / `_pct` / `_bps` / `_ms` suffix, no schema comment, no enclosing semantic-model definition): run `execute_sql` to inspect the value range before authoring any aggregate over it.

```sql
SELECT MIN(<col>) AS lo, MAX(<col>) AS hi, AVG(<col>) AS mid FROM <table>;
-- optionally sample a few rows for full context:
SELECT <col> FROM <table> ORDER BY RANDOM() LIMIT 10;
```

Cross-check the result against **business plausibility** for the domain:
- An AOV at a sandwich shop of `1250` is almost certainly cents-stored. An AOV of `12.50` is plausibly dollars-stored.
- A `latency` median of `420` is almost certainly milliseconds. `0.42` is plausibly seconds.
- A `tax_rate` of `0.06` is a fraction. `6.0` is a percent-as-integer. `600` is basis points.

When the probe range disambiguates the unit, commit to that interpretation and **state it inline** as a SQL comment near the cast / arithmetic (`-- order_total is cents; divide by 100 for USD`) so a reader doesn't have to re-derive your reasoning.

When the probe range does **not** disambiguate (e.g. all values are integers between 100 and 10000 — could be cents-USD or dollars-thousands), do not silently pick the convention your training data is most familiar with. Two coexisting LLMs on the same prompt + same dataset have been observed to pick opposite units (one cents, one dollars), producing dashboards whose grand totals differ by 100×. This is **exactly the case** the `ask_user` tool exists for — surface the ambiguity to the human, even though the prompt's general guidance leans against asking when you can infer.

### Visual design

Treat each output as a polished deliverable — a small **branded analytics product** for dashboards, a **research-style document** for reports. Quality bar:

- **Cohesive palette** at the top of a shared module (`render/shared/colors.js` or inline in `app.jsx`) as a `COLORS` const (primary, secondary, accent, navy/heading, background, text, muted, positive, negative). Pick a palette that fits the domain.
- **Map categorical dimensions to consistent colors** via dedicated constants (`REGION_COLORS`, `SEGMENT_COLORS`, `STATUS_COLORS`, …). Reuse the same color for the same category across every chart.
- **Inline styles only** for layout and chrome — no Tailwind utility classes for layout, no external stylesheets. Use `style={{ ... }}` objects for everything visual.
- **Card primitive** comes from `@datus/web-artifact` as `<ChartCard>` — the same surface every dashboard uses (white background, 12px border-radius, asymmetric `padding: '20px 20px 16px'`, subtle shadow, flex-column stretch + border-box sizing). Wrap every chart panel in it. ChartCard already lays out the title strip + chart-actions menu and exposes `style` / `className` for the rare cases you need to nudge dimensions.
- **Responsive grid**: `display: 'grid', gridTemplateColumns: 'repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr))', gridAutoRows: '1fr', gap: 16`. `gridAutoRows: '1fr'` is mandatory: without it, each row's height tracks every card's own content, so a row that mixes a chart with `<Legend>` (or with an extra footer / pagination row) against one without will visibly misalign at the bottom. Combined with the flex-column ChartCard primitive, every card in a row stretches to the tallest card's height and bottoms line up across the row.
- **Typography**: 22px/700 H1, 14px/600 card titles, 24px/700 KPI numbers, 11–13px secondary text.
- **KPI sparklines** (dashboard mode): small `<Sparkline>` component using `AreaChart` with vertical gradient fill (5%–95% opacity stops) and 2-px stroke in the primary color.
- **Comparison badges** (dashboard mode): pill-shaped `▲ 12%` / `▼ 8%` chips next to KPIs using positive/negative semantic colors.
- **Custom SVG visualizations are encouraged** when Recharts can't express the idea: treemaps, chord diagrams, semicircle gauges, score sliders, etc. Implement with hand-rolled `<svg>` paths and `useMemo` for layout math.
- **Report prose typography** (report mode): body text at 15px / 1.6 line-height inside `maxWidth: 720` for comfortable reading. H2 at 18px/600 with a thin bottom border in the primary color; H3 at 14px/600 with extra top margin.
- **Section primitive** (report mode): a `<Section>` wrapper with optional kicker, title, and body slot. Insert a subtle divider rule between sections.
- **Callout / pull-quote primitive** (report mode): a `<Callout>` block with a 4-px left border in `COLORS.primary` (or `accent` / `negative`), pale background. At most one per section.
- **Figure captions** (report mode): every chart gets a caption beneath the `<ResponsiveContainer>` in the form `Figure N. <one-line description>. Source: <sqlId>, executed <date>`. Captions in 11px italic muted text.
- **Data tables**: zebra-striped rows, right-aligned numeric columns, left-aligned string columns, sticky header within the table card. When the dataset has **more than 15 rows, paginate** at 15 rows/page. Render a small pagination footer beneath the table — `‹ Prev`, `<current> / <total>` indicator, `Next ›` laid out in a single row and **right-aligned within the card** (`display: 'flex', justifyContent: 'flex-end', alignItems: 'center', gap: 8`). Never center the footer in the card or stretch it edge-to-edge — flex-end is mandatory so multiple tables on the same page align visually. Keep the current page in component-local `useState`; disable the boundary button at page 1 / last page. Don't use a "show more" toggle and don't render all rows at once; paginating is the cleaner read for the user and keeps the rendered DOM small.

### Loading & error placeholders — `Skeleton` / `ErrorBlock`

`Skeleton` and `ErrorBlock` are runtime-provided primitives — **import them directly from `@datus/web-artifact`**. Do not re-implement them; every artifact shares one canonical look and gets free upgrades when the runtime ships new versions, exactly like `ChartCard` and `AnimateOnVisible`.

```jsx
import { useDatusArtifact, Skeleton, ErrorBlock } from '@datus/web-artifact';

function RevenueCard({ params }) {
  const { useQuerySql } = useDatusArtifact();
  const { isLoading, errorMessage, data, refetch } = useQuerySql('queries/foo', params);
  if (isLoading) return <Skeleton minHeight={300} />;
  if (errorMessage) return <ErrorBlock msg={errorMessage} onRetry={refetch} />;
  // ... chart JSX
}
```

Props:

| Component | Prop | Default | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| `Skeleton` | `minHeight` | `200` | Match the chart's expected height so the layout doesn't shift when real content mounts. |
| `Skeleton` | `bars` | `3` | Number of shimmer bars (60% / 80% / 40% width cycle). Bump to 4–5 for taller cards. |
| `ErrorBlock` | `msg` | — (required) | The `errorMessage` field from `useQuerySql`. |
| `ErrorBlock` | `onRetry` | `window.location.reload` | Pass `refetch` from `useQuerySql` so the Retry button re-runs just the failed query instead of reloading the whole iframe. |
| `ErrorBlock` | `minHeight` | `140` | Override only when the surrounding layout demands a specific height. |

Rules:

- **Always wire `onRetry={refetch}`** in components that use `useQuerySql`. The fallback (`window.location.reload()`) re-mounts the entire artifact iframe and loses any local UI state (filters, page numbers, scroll position) — fine as a last resort but not the preferred path.
- **The placeholders use a fixed neutral palette** (gray-100/200 shimmer for `Skeleton`; red-50 / red-200 / red-700 for `ErrorBlock`) so error UX is consistent across every artifact. Do not try to override their colors via wrapper divs — if a future palette knob is needed, it will land as an explicit prop.
- **Lucide icons inside the runtime placeholders** (`AlertCircle`, `RotateCcw`) are part of the component, not something you import — they are an exception to the "icons sparingly" rule below because the placeholders are functional UI.

### Iconography & emoji

- **No emoji anywhere in the artifact.** Not in headings, KPI titles, key-finding bullets, callouts, captions, or section kickers. Emoji render inconsistently across platforms, can't match the palette, and undercut the analytical credibility a BI deliverable needs.
- **Use Lucide icons sparingly.** Only in three places:
  1. **KPI card** — one icon left of the title, `16×16`, `strokeWidth={2}`, color `COLORS.muted`.
  2. **Section heading** (report mode) — one icon left of an H2, `18×18`, `strokeWidth={2}`, color `COLORS.primary`. Optional.
  3. **Trend / status pill** — inline next to a delta, `12–14px`, color tied to semantic state (`COLORS.positive` / `negative` / `warning`).
- **Never use icons** as bullet markers, in body prose, at sizes >24px (28px max for a hero KPI), or more than once per card. If a card needs two icons, the card is doing too much.
- **Lucide style defaults**: `strokeWidth={2}` (thinner gets fuzzy on retina), color via inline `style={{ color }}`, no shadow / rotation / `fill` (Lucide is stroke-based; filling makes a blob).
- **Emoji → Lucide substitution table** — when you reach for an emoji, pick the Lucide name instead:

  | Emoji impulse | Lucide name |
  |---|---|
  | 📈 / 📉 | `TrendingUp` / `TrendingDown` |
  | 📊 | `BarChart3` / `LineChart` |
  | 💰 / 💵 | `Banknote` / `DollarSign` / `Wallet` |
  | 🌍 / 🌐 | `Globe` / `MapPin` |
  | 🏦 / 🏢 | `Landmark` / `Building2` |
  | 📱 | `Smartphone` |
  | 👥 / 🧑 | `Users` / `User` |
  | ⚡ | `Zap` |
  | ⚠️ | `TriangleAlert` |
  | ✅ / ❌ / ℹ️ | `CircleCheck` / `CircleX` / `Info` |
  | 🔍 / 📅 / 🎯 / 🔔 / ⏰ | `Search` / `Calendar` / `Target` / `Bell` / `Clock` |

  When in doubt, prefer no icon over a wrong one.

### Motion & animation

Charts enter with motion when the reader first scrolls them into view — a chart that finished animating off-screen feels as dead as a frozen one. Keep Recharts' built-in entrance animations on; defer the mount until first-viewport-entry via the shared `AnimateOnVisible` wrapper.

- **Don't disable Recharts defaults.** Never pass `isAnimationActive={false}` to `<Bar>` / `<Line>` / `<Area>` / `<Pie>` / `<Radar>` / `<Scatter>`. If you want no motion, omit the chart.
- **Tune via three props** on each animated primitive: `animationDuration` (default `1500`ms — use `800–1200` for KPI sparklines, `1500–2000` for hero charts), `animationEasing` (prefer `'ease-out'` for entrances), `animationBegin` (default `0` — stagger related series by `index * 80–250` ms so the eye reads each one separately).
- **Defer the mount until viewport entry.** Wrap every animated visualization in `AnimateOnVisible` from `@datus/web-artifact` — it has correct `IntersectionObserver` defaults (`rootMargin: '0px 0px -10% 0px'`, `threshold: 0.1`), disconnects after first hit, and reserves vertical space via `minHeight` so layout doesn't shift on mount. Do **not** write your own `useInView` hook.

```jsx
import { useDatusArtifact, ChartCard, AnimateOnVisible } from '@datus/web-artifact';
import { LineChart, Line, ResponsiveContainer, XAxis, YAxis, Tooltip } from 'recharts';

function RevenueTrend() {
  const { useQuerySql } = useDatusArtifact();
  const { data } = useQuerySql('queries/revenue_by_month');
  const rows = data?.rows ?? [];

  return (
    <ChartCard
      cardId="revenue_by_month"
      sqlId="queries/revenue_by_month"
      chartType="line"
      title="Revenue trend"
      data={data}
    >
      <AnimateOnVisible minHeight={300}>
        <ResponsiveContainer width="100%" height={300}>
          <LineChart data={rows}>
            <XAxis dataKey="month" />
            <YAxis />
            <Tooltip />
            <Line type="monotone" dataKey="revenue" stroke="#6051F5" />
          </LineChart>
        </ResponsiveContainer>
      </AnimateOnVisible>
    </ChartCard>
  );
}
```

`AnimateOnVisible` props (all optional):

| Prop | Default | When to override |
|---|---|---|
| `minHeight` | `320` | Set to the chart's `<ResponsiveContainer height>`. A wrong value causes a layout jump when the chart mounts. |
| `immediate` | `false` | Set to `true` for an above-the-fold chart you want to animate without waiting for the observer, or as a `prefers-reduced-motion` escape hatch. |

Rules:
- **One `AnimateOnVisible` per chart panel**, not one wrapping the whole artifact.
- **Reserve `minHeight`** equal to the chart's `<ResponsiveContainer height>` — otherwise the page jumps when the chart mounts.
- **Custom inline SVG** (treemaps, gauges): also wrap in `AnimateOnVisible`; inside, animate `transform` / `opacity` / `stroke-dashoffset` via CSS transitions toggled by a mount `useState` + `useEffect(() => setMounted(true), [])`.
- **Respect reduced motion.** Compute `window.matchMedia('(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)').matches` once in `app.jsx` and pass `animationDuration={prefersReducedMotion ? 0 : 1500}` to Recharts primitives. `AnimateOnVisible` stays on — it only delays mount, never adds motion.

### Chart action menu

ChartCard embeds the chart-actions menu (View SQL / Export SQL / CSV / JSON / PNG / Copy PNG) — you don't import or wire `ChartEntryMore` yourself. ChartCard reads `sqlId` + `data` straight from its own props and owns the screenshot root, so PNG export captures the title + chart together with no `cardRef` plumbing on your side.

**One ChartCard per card.** When a card visualizes more than one sub-view (e.g. two side-by-side pies sharing one query), wrap them in a single `<ChartCard>` whose body is a 2-column grid — not two adjacent ChartCards.

**Attach a ChartCard to every `useQuerySql`-backed visualization** — charts, KPI cards, custom SVG, **and data tables** (the table goes inside the ChartCard body, including the header strip; the chart-actions menu lives in the ChartCard's title strip above it).

If you genuinely need to render a card without the chart-actions menu (filter strip, decorative banner, etc.), set `hideMenu` on the ChartCard. Direct use of the standalone `ChartEntryMore` import is reserved for the rare custom case where ChartCard's chrome doesn't fit — almost never required.

### Formatting helpers

Centralise formatters in a shared module (e.g. `render/shared/formatters.js`) and import them where needed:

```js
import { format as d3Format } from 'd3-format';
import dayjs from 'dayjs';

export const N = (v) => (v != null ? Number(v) : 0);
export const pctChange = (cur, prior) => (prior === 0 ? 0 : (cur - prior) / prior);

const _money = d3Format('$,.3~s');
const _count = d3Format(',.3~s');
const _int   = d3Format(',.0f');
const _pct   = d3Format('+.1%');

export const formatCurrency = (v) => _money(N(v)).replace('k', 'K');
export const formatNumber   = (v) => _count(N(v)).replace('k', 'K');
export const formatInt      = (v) => _int(N(v));
export const formatPct      = (v) => _pct(N(v));

export const formatMonth = (v) => dayjs(v).format('MMM YYYY');
export const formatDate  = (v) => dayjs(v).format('MMM D, YYYY');
```

Guidelines:
- Always coerce numeric cells with `N(...)` before arithmetic — BIGINT lands as JS `BigInt`, which breaks `Math.*` / `d3-format` / Recharts.
- Build `d3Format(spec)` specifiers at module scope (parses on every call otherwise).
- Pick the specifier from the column's semantic type: `integer` → `_int`, `number` → `_count` or `_money`, ratios stored as fractions → `_pct`.

### Sandbox constraints

The viewer iframe runs with `sandbox="allow-scripts"` only — null origin, no `allow-same-origin`. That means:
- No `window.parent` access. No `localStorage` / `sessionStorage`.
- No `fetch` — data comes only from `useQuerySql`.
- No `eval` / `new Function` in your code.
- No router — the rendered page is a single view.

Stick to React state for everything interactive.
